doc.after: 32% of San Francisco residents use public transportation in daily commuting to work, ranking it first on the West Coast and third overall in the United States.[262] The San Francisco Municipal Railway, known as Muni, is the primary public transit system of San Francisco. Muni is the seventh-largest transit system in the United States, with 210,848,310 rides in 2006.[263] The system operates both a combined light rail and subway system, the Muni Metro, and a large bus network.[264] Additionally, it runs a historic streetcar line, which runs on Market Street from Castro Street to Fisherman's Wharf.[264] It also operates the famous cable cars,[264] which have been designated as a National Historic Landmark and are a major tourist attraction.[265]
